{
  "designRationale": {
    "layoutDecisions": "The layout is vertically oriented, placing the top app bar at the top, followed by a scrollable section for product images and details, and concluding with the bottom navigation bar.  This flow prioritizes visual information before interactive elements.",
    "userFlowReasoning": "The user first sees the product images, then essential information (title, price), seller details, and finally, a clear call-to-action to contact the seller. Navigation allows easy movement between product listings and user profile.",
    "componentChoices": "I chose the `appbar` (10:5620) and `navigation` (10:4724) components for top and bottom navigation respectively, over using a custom header and footer because these components offer built-in styles and responsiveness. The `IMAGES` (10:7816) component is used for displaying product images to leverage its image handling capabilities over native image elements.",
    "componentGaps": "User request requires a seller avatar component combined with name and location which doesn't exist in the design system. I combined the `avatar` (10:7773) component with two `native-text` elements for name and location. This provides a visually consistent way of showcasing seller information.",
    "visualHierarchy": "The product title and price have the highest visual prominence, using the 'Headline/Large' text style. Seller information is secondary, using 'Title/Medium'. The 'Contact Seller' button is a prominent green filled button using the 'Button' component for easy discoverability. ",
    "variantSelectionRationale": "For the 'Contact Seller' button (10:3907), I selected the \"Filled\" type and \"Large\" size over \"Outlined\" and \"Small\" because it offers maximum visual impact and is consistent with other primary calls to action.  The `appbar` is set to `Type: Default` to show the title instead of a search field. ",
    "nativeElementJustification": "User request requires the display of seller's name and location in close proximity to the avatar component.  Available components do not allow for this specific arrangement. Therefore, `native-text` elements solve this by creating a customized layout of text elements adjacent to the avatar, while maintaining component-based interactions for the button and avatar."
  }
}
```

